  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Pi_{\\mu\\nu}(x,x')\n=\n\\left.\n\\frac{\\delta^2 W[A]}\n{\\delta A_\\mu(x)\\,\\delta A_\\nu(x')}\n\\right|_{A=0}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Transversality Constraint.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^\\mu \\Pi_{\\mu\\nu}(x,x')=0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $W[A]$ be the effective generating functional for a gauge field $A_\\mu$.  \nThe first variation of $W[A]$ measures linear response to a gauge perturbation.\n\nThe second variation extracts the vacuum response tensor:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Pi_{\\mu\\nu}(x,x')\n=\n\\left.\n\\frac{\\delta^2 W[A]}\n{\\delta A_\\mu(x)\\,\\delta A_\\nu(x')}\n\\right|_{A=0}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nGauge-compatible conservation requires the response tensor to be transverse:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^\\mu \\Pi_{\\mu\\nu}(x,x')=0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nVacuum polarization records how the vacuum screens, dresses, or responds to gauge excitation.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
